 Department of Social Work | Orientation Visit to Indian Social Institute (ISI), Bangalore

            <b class="panel-title pull-right">July 04<sup>th</sup> 2017</b>
            <div style="clear:both"></div>
        </div>
		<div class="panel-body">
		

            <p align=justify>The Department of Social Work of Kristu Jayanti College, Bangalore has organized an orientation visit for the third semester students to Indian Social Institute on the 4th of July, 2017. The students were lead by <b>Dr. Winnie Joyce A.</b> and <b>Dr. Emmanuel Daniel,</b> faculty members, Department of Social Work. On arrival, the students were given a presentation on the overview of the organization. The session began with <b>Fr. Selvaraj Arulnathan SJ</b>, Director, Indian Social Institute, addressing the Social Work students on the need to be in touch with the grass root realities of the times that we live in. He exhorted the students to be empathetic towards the need of the marginalized communities and work towards their progress. Moreover, <b>Fr.Francis Desouza,</b> Administrator, Indian Social Institute, added that the budding Social Workers should develop a passion for justice and have an analytical approach in their work. This was followed by a session by <b>Mr. Shujayathulla E</b>. Aashrafee, Research Assistant, ISI, wherein the origin of the institution, its objectives, values, and goals were imparted. <b>Ms. A.M Kanchana</b>, Assistant, Human Rights and Training Unit, ISI, handled the next session where she emphasized on the efforts taken by Indian Social Institute in the intervention of Human Rights in various social issues through collaborating with various like-minded organizations. Subsequently, <b>Ms. Sharda Sharma,</b> Co-ordinator, Women’s Unit, ISI, stressed on the various role of the Women’s Unit of ISI like organizing training programmes for NGO activists and representatives working with women of the backward communities, workshops on gender based violence and addressing the issue of gender sensitivity, to name a few. Eventually, Mr. Richard Gonsalves, Programme Manager, Labour and Migration Unit, ISI, highlighted on the initiatives taken by Labour and Migration Unit in securing the rights and entitlements of the migrant workers in South India. Furthermore, he brought to light the future plans of Indian Social Institute, Bangalore which includes conducting seminars on contemporary issues, Cadre building, capacity building, to name a few. </p>
            <p align=justify>The orientation visit came to a close with a vote of thanks by Ms. Kathy Biginchi Momin, II MSW. The Social Work students felt content having visited the organization as they acquired an understanding of the work nature of the organization in a profound manner.</p>



